<p>Shopify and Wix are two of the most popular website builders in 2026, but they serve different audiences and excel in different areas. Shopify is the undisputed leader in e-commerce, while Wix offers the most versatile general-purpose website building experience. Choosing between them depends on your specific goals, and this comprehensive comparison will help you make the right decision.</p>

<p>For a broader look at how these platforms stack up against other builders, check our <a href="/">full website builder comparison</a>.</p>

<h2>Ease of Use</h2>

<h3>Wix</h3>

<p>Wix offers one of the most intuitive drag-and-drop editors available. You can click on any element and move it anywhere on the page with complete freedom. The WYSIWYG editor shows your changes in real time, and there is no learning curve for basic editing tasks. Wix also provides an AI website builder that generates a complete site based on your answers to a few simple questions.</p>

<h3>Shopify</h3>

<p>Shopify's editor is straightforward but more structured than Wix. You work within predefined sections and blocks, which limits creative freedom but ensures your store always looks professional. The dashboard is well-organized with clear navigation for products, orders, customers, and analytics. However, beginners who just want a simple website may find Shopify's commerce-focused interface overly complex.</p>

<p><strong>Winner: Wix</strong> — For pure ease of use and design flexibility, Wix is the clear winner. If you are a <a href="/blog/best-website-builder-for-beginners">complete beginner</a>, Wix is more approachable.</p>

<h2>E-commerce Features</h2>

<h3>Shopify</h3>

<p>This is where Shopify truly shines. The platform was built from the ground up for selling online, and it shows. Key e-commerce features include multi-channel selling across Facebook, Instagram, Amazon, and eBay, a powerful inventory management system, built-in payment processing through Shopify Payments, automated tax calculations, real-time shipping rates from major carriers, abandoned cart recovery emails, and gift cards and discount codes.</p>

<p>Shopify also offers a massive app store with thousands of e-commerce focused extensions for everything from product reviews to subscription boxes to dropshipping integrations.</p>

<h3>Wix</h3>

<p>Wix has significantly improved its e-commerce capabilities in recent years. You can sell physical and digital products, manage inventory, accept payments through multiple gateways, and offer discount codes. However, Wix lacks some advanced features that serious online retailers need, such as multi-channel selling, advanced inventory management across multiple locations, and the depth of third-party e-commerce integrations that Shopify provides.</p>

<p><strong>Winner: Shopify</strong> — For serious online selling, Shopify is the superior choice. Read more in our <a href="/blog/best-ecommerce-website-builders">best e-commerce website builders guide</a>.</p>

<h2>Design and Templates</h2>

<h3>Wix</h3>

<p>Wix offers over 900 templates across dozens of categories, making it one of the most template-rich platforms available. Each template is fully customizable with pixel-perfect drag-and-drop control. You can change literally everything about a template, from layout structure to individual element positioning. Wix also lets you start from a blank canvas if you prefer to build from scratch.</p>

<h3>Shopify</h3>

<p>Shopify provides around 180 themes, with about 13 free options and the rest ranging from $150 to $400 for a one-time purchase. The themes are high-quality and optimized for conversions, but you have less design flexibility compared to Wix. Customization happens within a section-based editor that keeps your design structured and consistent.</p>

<p><strong>Winner: Wix</strong> — More templates, more design freedom, and no premium theme costs.</p>

<h2>Pricing Comparison</h2>

<p>Understanding the true cost of each platform is crucial. Here is how they compare on monthly pricing for their most popular plans.</p>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Wix Combo:</strong> $16/month — Suitable for personal sites with a custom domain</li>
  <li><strong>Wix Business:</strong> $27/month — Adds online payments and e-commerce features</li>
  <li><strong>Shopify Basic:</strong> $39/month — Full e-commerce with 2% transaction fee on third-party payments</li>
  <li><strong>Shopify Standard:</strong> $105/month — Lower transaction fees and more staff accounts</li>
</ul>

<p>Wix is significantly cheaper for basic websites and light e-commerce. Shopify costs more but provides enterprise-grade selling tools. For a detailed cost analysis, see our <a href="/blog/website-builder-pricing-guide">website builder pricing guide</a>.</p>

<h2>SEO and Marketing</h2>

<p>Both platforms offer solid SEO tools including custom meta titles and descriptions, alt text for images, clean URLs, and XML sitemaps. Wix has closed the gap with Shopify on SEO and now offers comparable performance for search engine optimization.</p>

<p>For email marketing, Shopify includes built-in email campaigns through Shopify Email, while Wix offers Wix Email Marketing. Both integrate with third-party tools like Mailchimp and Klaviyo. Learn more about optimizing your site in our <a href="/blog/website-builder-seo-guide">website builder SEO guide</a>.</p>

<h2>Customer Support</h2>

<p>Shopify offers 24/7 support via live chat, email, and phone across all plans. Their support team is highly knowledgeable about e-commerce topics. Wix provides 24/7 support through a callback system and chat, with priority support for higher-tier plans. Both platforms maintain extensive knowledge bases and community forums.</p>

<h2>Which One Should You Choose?</h2>

<p>The decision comes down to your primary goal.</p>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Choose Wix if:</strong> You want a general-purpose website with maximum design flexibility, you are on a tighter budget, you need a portfolio or blog, or your e-commerce needs are modest</li>
  <li><strong>Choose Shopify if:</strong> Selling products online is your primary focus, you plan to sell across multiple channels, you need advanced inventory and shipping tools, or you anticipate high sales volume</li>
</ul>

<p>Both platforms are excellent in their respective strengths. Visit our <a href="/">website builder comparison page</a> to see how Shopify and Wix compare against other leading platforms and find your ideal match.</p>

